{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17532188","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17532188"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T16:23:45+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T16:23:45+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14658"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14658","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14658"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.35,0.22,0.04,0.1,0.29]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7351"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"99459"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7351","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7351"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14658"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"81846"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"28"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"98"},{"type":"tags","id":"2436"},{"type":"tags","id":"4040"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"12912"},{"type":"tags","id":"12921"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"17939"},{"type":"contributions","id":"28726"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"99459","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/99459"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn 81-year-old man is admitted to hospital under the palliative care team with end-stage renal failure. He has been deteriorating over the past week, spending more time sleeping. He has a medical history of hypertension and type 2 diabetes. His regular medications have been ceased due to his declining condition.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOver the past four hours, he has become increasingly agitated and distressed by noisy secretions in his airways. His consciousness level is fluctuating. On examination, he appears uncomfortable and restless. His pulse rate is 102/min, blood pressure 145/90 mmHg, respiratory rate 24/min, SpO2 92% on room air, and temperature 36.5\u00b0C. Chest auscultation reveals loud upper airway secretions with coarse bubbling sounds, but clear lung fields.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Start hyoscine hydrobromide","Position patient upright","Commence nebulised saline","Explain and reassure family","Regular oral care and suctioning"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis scenario describes death rattle, which is the noise created by oscillation of secretions in the upper airways of dying patients who are too weak to clear them effectively. In this case, the secretions are causing significant patient distress, indicating the need for pharmacological intervention.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStart hyoscine hydrobromide\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate first step as it will help reduce secretion production through its anticholinergic effects. Anticholinergic medications are most effective when started early, before secretions become too severe. The medication can be given subcutaneously as either a bolus or continuous infusion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPosition patient upright\u003C/strong\u003E may provide some temporary relief but would not address the underlying problem of excessive secretion production. Additionally, repositioning may cause further distress to an already agitated patient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECommence nebulised saline\u003C/strong\u003E would be counterproductive as it would increase airway secretions and potentially worsen the situation. Nebulised saline is sometimes used to help mobilise thick secretions in patients who can effectively cough and clear their airways, which is not the case here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EExplain and reassure family\u003C/strong\u003E is important but should not delay active management when the patient is showing signs of distress. While death rattle can be distressing for families to witness, addressing the patient\u0027s immediate comfort takes priority.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERegular oral care and suctioning\u003C/strong\u003E may be traumatic and distressing for the patient at this stage. Suctioning can stimulate more secretion production and cause additional discomfort without providing lasting benefit.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDeath rattle occurs in up to 50% of dying patients. While it is often more distressing to witnesses than to the patient themselves, when accompanied by agitation (as in this case), pharmacological management is indicated. The key principle is to treat early when intervention is needed, as anticholinergics can prevent further secretion formation but cannot clear existing secretions.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Death rattle is a common end-of-life symptom caused by accumulated secretions in the airways of dying patients who are too weak to clear them.","Anticholinergic medications like hyoscine hydrobromide are first-line treatment when secretions cause patient distress.","Early intervention with anticholinergics is more effective than waiting until secretions become severe."],"references":["Siegel M, Bigelow S. Palliative care symptom management in the emergency department: the ABC\u0027s of symptom management for the emergency physician. The Journal of Emergency Medicine. 2018 Jan 1;54(1):25-32. Available online at ; https://www.jem-journal.com/article/S0736-4679(17)30705-9/fulltext"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"81846"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14658"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"81846","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/81846"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-20T21:13:30+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-20T21:14:39+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7351"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"99459"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"28","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/28"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc95","name":"Palliative Care","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"78","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/78"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level III","synonyms":null,"description":"Apply, analyze, evaluate, and create (implementing, organizing, and critiquing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"98","links":{"self":"https://app